{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636675"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:31:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:31:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17596"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17596"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10310"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115237"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10310"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17596"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97245"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5395"},{"type":"tags","id":"5462"},{"type":"tags","id":"5482"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24104"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24108"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115237"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher is planning to document the clinical features and outcomes of patients with a newly identified rare genetic disorder at their hospital.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the key characteristics of a case series study design?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Matches cases with healthy controls","Randomly assigns participants to different interventions","Compares outcomes between exposed and unexposed groups","Surveys population prevalence at a single time point","Follows a group of similar patients over time without a control group"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecase series follows a group of similar patients over time without a control group\u003C/strong\u003E. This study design is particularly useful for describing rare conditions, documenting novel presentations or treatments, and generating hypotheses for future research. However, without a control group, case series cannot establish causation or compare effectiveness of interventions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompares outcomes between exposed and unexposed groups\u003C/strong\u003E describes a cohort study design. \u003Cstrong\u003ERandomly assigns participants to different interventions\u003C/strong\u003E describes a randomised controlled trial. \u003Cstrong\u003EMatches cases with healthy controls\u003C/strong\u003E describes a case-control study design. \u003Cstrong\u003ESurveys population prevalence at a single time point\u003C/strong\u003E describes a cross-sectional study design.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECase series sit low in the hierarchy of evidence due to their observational nature and lack of control group. However, they play an important role in initial description of new conditions and hypothesis generation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Case series are observational studies that follow a group of patients with a particular condition or exposure over time.","Case series lack a control group and cannot establish causation or compare interventions.","Case series are useful for describing rare conditions, generating hypotheses, and documenting novel presentations or treatments."],"references":["Weaver A, Goldberg S. Clinical Biostatistics and Epidemiology Made Ridiculously Simple. Miami: MedMaster; 2012. Chapter 5; pg. 25.","Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Bu